WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.994
[SWOOSHING]

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:12.070
We're all human.

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:14.480
And yet we all look different.

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:18.520
Now, a lot about the way
we look is down to our DNA,

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:22.600
as we can see so brilliantly
with these identical twins.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:26.560
From eye colour to hair
colour to dimples to height,

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.980
each pair of twins
looks very similar.

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:32.439
But look a little more
closely, and you'll

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:37.120
see that each person
here is unique.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.930
In this lecture, we'll explore
how much of the differences

00:00:40.930 --> 00:00:44.440
between us are down
to genes and how much

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:47.050
is due to everything else.

00:00:47.050 --> 00:00:51.209
We'll be looking at
what makes you unique.

00:00:51.209 --> 00:00:54.203
[BUBBLING]

00:00:54.203 --> 00:00:57.197
[GROANING]

00:01:07.177 --> 00:01:10.171
[CRINKLING]

00:01:10.171 --> 00:01:13.165
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:21.149 --> 00:01:23.880
I am Professor Alice Roberts.

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:27.750
Welcome to the third of this
year's Royal Institution

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:29.340
Christmas Lectures.

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:32.790
And this lecture is all
about us as a species.

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:36.450
It's all about human diversity.

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:40.980
But first, let's start off
with a different species

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:42.945
which is very diverse indeed.

00:01:46.932 --> 00:01:48.770
You stand here.

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:53.090
So we've got an amazing
range of different dogs here.

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:58.280
And the astonishing thing about
this is that they are all dogs.

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:00.830
They all belong to
the same species.

00:02:00.830 --> 00:02:03.570
And yet they look so incredibly
different from each other.

00:02:03.570 --> 00:02:06.620
We've got to we've got a Great
Dane, got a little Shih Tzu,

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:09.280
and a tiny little
miniature dachshund.

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:12.740
Now, isn't it amazing that
there's all that variation

00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:14.210
in one species?

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:16.550
Humans first started
domesticating dogs

00:02:16.550 --> 00:02:19.610
about 30,000 years
ago, when our ancestors

00:02:19.610 --> 00:02:21.770
were hunter-gatherers.

00:02:21.770 --> 00:02:24.800
And then over
thousands of years,

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:28.730
we've somehow moulded
all of these changes.

00:02:28.730 --> 00:02:31.700
So we've bred dogs
that are really

00:02:31.700 --> 00:02:34.040
good at going down burrows
and chasing animals,

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:35.420
like the dachshund.

00:02:35.420 --> 00:02:37.760
And this is all down
to us interacting

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:39.680
with this other species.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:42.710
Now, to explore this diversity
and how it comes about

00:02:42.710 --> 00:02:44.270
in more detail, I
need to introduce

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:49.945
one more species and, my friend,
geneticist Professor Aoife

00:02:49.945 --> 00:02:50.445
McLysaght.

00:02:50.445 --> 00:02:53.230
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:56.562 --> 00:02:59.610
It wasn't entirely clear
if you were referring to me

00:02:59.610 --> 00:03:02.070
as the additional species
or this beautiful chihuahua

00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:03.060
in my arms.

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:06.300
But this Chihuahua, of course,
was bred as a companion dog.

00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:08.280
And you can see,
he's very, very cute.

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:10.620
And dogs are especially
interesting in terms

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:13.790
of genetics because
this huge diversity

00:03:13.790 --> 00:03:15.540
that we can see in
front of us is actually

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:18.630
down to quite a small
amount of genetic diversity.

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:20.980
They are, after all,
just one species.

00:03:20.980 --> 00:03:22.920
And that makes it
much easier to be

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:27.300
able to figure out how the
genes contribute to the changes

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:29.240
that we can actually
see on the outside.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:30.990
And so for example,
this little Chihuahua,

00:03:30.990 --> 00:03:33.390
and other miniature
dogs like this,

00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:36.690
the size variation is
largely down to just changes

00:03:36.690 --> 00:03:38.700
in just one gene.

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:41.503
Now, we are actually able to
understand the genetic basis

00:03:41.503 --> 00:03:42.170
of some of this?

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:42.670
Yeah.

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:44.310
So many of the origins
of these traits

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:46.250
has been traced genetically.

00:03:46.250 --> 00:03:50.670
So we can get a real handle
on how variation in our genes

00:03:50.670 --> 00:03:53.460
contributes to the kind of
variance that we can see.

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:55.950
So let's have a think about
how all of this variation

00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:56.710
comes about.

00:03:56.710 --> 00:03:58.980
But for now, let's say
"thank you very much"

00:03:58.980 --> 00:04:00.500
to our brilliant dog lineup.

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:01.949
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:01.949 --> 00:04:02.915
Here we go.

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:11.370
So all those
differences have been

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:14.040
bred into different
breeds of dogs

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:17.100
by breeders choosing
dogs of particular traits

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:19.950
and then breeding them on
to the next generation.

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:22.019
That's something called
selective breeding.

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:25.410
It's what Charles Darwin
called artificial selection.

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:27.570
And he imagined how
he could continue

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:29.130
thinking about
this to see, well,

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.050
does this happen
in nature, as well?

00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:33.300
How do we get natural selection?

00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:34.800
And to really
explain this, we're

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:36.690
going to play a
game with this demo.

00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:39.340
And we need two volunteers.

00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:39.840
OK.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:41.040
Let's see.

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:41.540
Yes?

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:42.480
You there in the lovely jumper.

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:43.230
Lovely Christmas jumper.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:43.818
Come on down.

00:04:43.818 --> 00:04:45.360
And also put one
down there, as well.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:45.860
Great.

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:47.070
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:47.070 --> 00:04:48.540
So are you excited?

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:49.410
Freddy.

00:04:49.410 --> 00:04:49.910
Freddy.

00:04:49.910 --> 00:04:51.050
Lovely to meet you, Freddy.

00:04:51.050 --> 00:04:51.770
And what's your name?

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:52.270
Rebecca.

00:04:52.270 --> 00:04:53.360
Rebecca.

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:56.570
So what you see beside
you here are two habitats.

00:04:56.570 --> 00:04:59.330
And you can see very
quickly that this is mainly

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:00.200
orange habitat.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:01.610
The floor is orange.

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:04.100
And it's filled with these
balloons, which are mostly what

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:05.840
we're calling "orange pebbles."

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:08.390
And over there, we've got a
grey habitat with grey floor

00:05:08.390 --> 00:05:09.560
and grey pebbles.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:14.490
But in amongst the pebbles,
there is something else.

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:16.820
So here we have a mouse.

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:20.990
And there's orange and grey
mice in each of these habitats.

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:24.620
And so we're going to
put these in there.

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:27.770
And Freddy, what
we didn't tell you

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:29.720
is that your job is to
actually be a predator.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:30.980
You need to catch some mice.

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:32.970
And you need to catch
some mice, as well.

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:34.640
So you're going to
have to go in there.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:37.070
And I want you to catch
mice but not pebbles.

00:05:37.070 --> 00:05:38.510
So you can go around the back.

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:39.810
And just the ones
with faces, all right?

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:40.070
Yeah.

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:41.490
So only the ones with
faces we're interested in.

00:05:41.490 --> 00:05:43.650
If you go around the
back, they'll let you in.

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:44.150
Yeah.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:46.108
So don't start catching
mice yet because that's

00:05:46.108 --> 00:05:47.180
far too easy, actually.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:47.680
Yeah.

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:48.860
Let's make make
them more energetic.

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:49.010
Yeah.

00:05:49.010 --> 00:05:51.302
We need to make something a
bit more difficult for you.

00:05:51.302 --> 00:05:54.090
[ROARING]

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:56.240
So on our marks at--
well, we'll count down.

00:05:56.240 --> 00:05:56.965
3--

00:05:56.965 --> 00:05:58.508
(ALL) 2, 1.

00:05:58.508 --> 00:05:59.008
Go.

00:05:59.008 --> 00:06:01.996
[WHIMSICAL MUSIC]

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:18.926
(TOGETHER) 3, 2, 1.

00:06:18.926 --> 00:06:19.426
Stop.

00:06:19.426 --> 00:06:21.914
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:21.914 --> 00:06:22.414
OK.

00:06:22.414 --> 00:06:23.906
You can come out.

00:06:23.906 --> 00:06:24.406
OK.

00:06:24.406 --> 00:06:24.904
You can come back out.

00:06:24.904 --> 00:06:26.237
Come around and see how you did.

00:06:26.237 --> 00:06:28.390
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:28.390 --> 00:06:30.150
How was that?

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:30.650
OK.

00:06:30.650 --> 00:06:31.400
Let's have a look.

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:32.510
Well, that's a mouse.

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:33.680
These are pebbles.

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:35.000
So we'll put those back.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:36.710
And if you've
gotten your rocks--

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:40.460
We've managed to catch four
orange mice and just one grey

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:40.960
mouse.

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:42.960
Well, Freddy managed
to catch one of each.

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:44.210
So what did you think, Freddy?

00:06:44.210 --> 00:06:46.040
What did you think of trying
to catch the mice in there?

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:46.640
What was it like?

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:47.150
Hard.

00:06:47.150 --> 00:06:47.800
Was it hard?

00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:50.120
Were either colour easier?

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:51.650
Not really, no.

00:06:51.650 --> 00:06:53.520
What about you over there?

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:55.078
Oh, it was easy.

00:06:55.078 --> 00:06:57.370
It was easier to see the
orange on the grey background.

00:06:57.370 --> 00:06:59.630
Yeah, you were going after
the orange ones, weren't you?

00:06:59.630 --> 00:06:59.820
Yeah.

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:01.320
And this is kind
of what we expect.

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:03.170
We see that naturally.

00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:06.290
In parts of the world where
we have kind of black rocks,

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:07.940
you tend to find
more black mice.

00:07:07.940 --> 00:07:09.410
And in parts of the world
where you have these golden,

00:07:09.410 --> 00:07:11.600
sandy rocks, we tend
to find these yellow,

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.880
sandy-coloured mice
because what we expect,

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:16.280
especially in the grey
habitat over there,

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:19.370
the orange mice were picked
off quite easily by this fierce

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:20.090
predator.

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:24.950
And the grey mice actually have
survived to live another day

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:26.840
and to pass on their genes.

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:29.070
But we did ask you
to be a predator.

00:07:29.070 --> 00:07:29.570
We did.

00:07:29.570 --> 00:07:30.920
You haven't quite finished
the job, have you?

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:31.420
No.

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:33.100
Could you stomp on those
balloons for me, please?

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:33.300
Go on.

00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:33.842
Have a stomp.

00:07:33.842 --> 00:07:34.762
[POUNDING]

00:07:34.762 --> 00:07:36.692
Yes!

00:07:36.692 --> 00:07:37.192
Yeah!

00:07:37.192 --> 00:07:38.650
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:40.108
Thank you so much.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.930
So artificial selection has
created all the dog breeds

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:51.130
that we see today.

00:07:51.130 --> 00:07:55.320
Natural selection picks
off some orange mice

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:57.170
in that demonstration.

00:07:57.170 --> 00:08:01.220
And natural selection has also
acted on us humans, as well.

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:05.230
So our species originated in
Africa hundreds of thousands

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:05.830
of years ago.

00:08:05.830 --> 00:08:09.380
But then we spread out of
Africa and colonised the globe,

00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:12.880
so we encountered all sorts
of different environments

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:13.990
as we went.

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:16.900
And there are lots of
ways that humans can fit

00:08:16.900 --> 00:08:18.580
into different environments.

00:08:18.580 --> 00:08:21.020
We're quite clever, so
we can create culture.

00:08:21.020 --> 00:08:22.150
And that can help us.

00:08:22.150 --> 00:08:24.100
So if we move into
a cold place, we

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:27.010
might make ourselves
warm clothes to put on.

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:29.560
There's also a
physiological adaptation.

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:31.600
And that means
that your body can

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:34.510
get used to an environment
over your lifetime.

00:08:34.510 --> 00:08:38.320
But you don't pass those kind
of changes on to your children.

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:42.700
So natural selection is when
there is a genetic difference

00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:44.640
generation by generation.

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:48.100
And we can see some great
examples of that in us humans.

00:08:48.100 --> 00:08:51.580
And one really good example
comes through the variation

00:08:51.580 --> 00:08:54.450
that we can see in skin colour.

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:57.250
And it tends to
map onto geography.

00:08:57.250 --> 00:09:00.760
Now, most of us tend to have a
fairly consistent skin colour

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:03.460
that we've inherited from
our parents and from earlier

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:04.540
ancestors.

00:09:04.540 --> 00:09:08.680
So over most of your body, your
skin colour is fairly similar.

00:09:08.680 --> 00:09:12.100
But I want to introduce you
to somebody now who's got very

00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:15.820
striking differences in
skin colour across his body.

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:19.420
And he is fashion
model Bashir Aziz.

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:21.408
[APPLAUSE]

00:09:21.408 --> 00:09:23.351
Bashir, hello.

00:09:23.351 --> 00:09:23.893
Much respect.

00:09:23.893 --> 00:09:24.887
Fantastic.

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:32.850
Bashir, you've got a
really striking look.

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:36.300
You've got two completely
different colours of skin

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:37.210
and hair, as well.

00:09:37.210 --> 00:09:39.010
So how long have you had that?

00:09:39.010 --> 00:09:40.000
Were you born like it?

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:41.030
Yeah, all my life.

00:09:41.030 --> 00:09:42.245
So that's what I've known.

00:09:42.245 --> 00:09:43.870
So across your body,
you've got areas--

00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:45.500
and obviously, we
can see on your face,

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:48.308
you've got areas quite pale skin
and then dark skin, as well.

00:09:48.308 --> 00:09:49.600
I mean, look at your arm there.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:50.100
Yeah.

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:51.700
So you've got a real mixture.

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:52.200
Yeah.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:54.700
So we can actually have a look
and see how much skin pigment

00:09:54.700 --> 00:09:56.500
you've got in different areas.

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.580
So we can use this
instrument here.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:09:59.080
So yeah.

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:02.380
Have look at the back
of your hand there.

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:04.240
And there we go.

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:08.470
So that says you've got 70%
skin pigment on that area.

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.900
Let's have a look at areas of
your skin that's pale, then.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:12.512
Can I try it on that area there?

00:10:12.512 --> 00:10:14.470
If I just pop it on there,
it should just work.

00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:14.720
Yeah.

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:15.910
See, look at a different there.

00:10:15.910 --> 00:10:16.750
That's astonishing.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:20.560
So where you've got pale skin,
there's only, what, about 9%--

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:21.130
9%.

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:21.640
--pigment.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:23.270
So really, really
big difference.

00:10:23.270 --> 00:10:26.950
So Bashir, we've got slides
here of pale skin-- rather

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:29.723
like the pale areas you've got--
and then dark skin, as well.

00:10:29.723 --> 00:10:32.140
And you can see that they're
very different when you first

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:33.100
look at them.

00:10:33.100 --> 00:10:37.150
And this difference is all to do
with the skin pigment melanin.

00:10:37.150 --> 00:10:41.230
And there are very few granules
of melanin in this skin.

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:43.180
But you can see, in
this section here,

00:10:43.180 --> 00:10:46.630
all of those cells completely
packed full of lots

00:10:46.630 --> 00:10:49.407
and lots of melanin granules.

00:10:49.407 --> 00:10:50.740
I'm going to try on me, as well.

00:10:50.740 --> 00:10:50.990
Go on.

00:10:50.990 --> 00:10:51.210
Go on.

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:52.210
And let's see what--

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:53.300
let's see what I've got.

00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:55.753
There's a little bit
of melanin in there.

00:10:55.753 --> 00:10:56.253
19.

00:10:56.253 --> 00:10:56.967
19.

00:10:56.967 --> 00:10:57.550
There you are.

00:10:57.550 --> 00:10:58.810
Well it is my hand,
