00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:01.170
That's all right.

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:04.750
So do you notice any difference
between your dark skin

00:11:04.750 --> 00:11:05.650
and your light skin?

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:06.775
What, as in like naturally?

00:11:06.775 --> 00:11:09.317
When you're exposed to the sun,
do you notice any difference?

00:11:09.317 --> 00:11:10.400
Do I see any difference?

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:11.560
I don't feel a difference.

00:11:11.560 --> 00:11:12.860
I don't notice a difference.

00:11:12.860 --> 00:11:16.000
I just walk the walk
and talk the talk.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.830
I would like, say,
put a little sunscreen

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:19.620
if it was very,
very, very sunny.

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:20.120
So--

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:22.328
So it's interesting because
the difference in pigment

00:11:22.328 --> 00:11:24.730
and the kind of pigment that's
there to begin with anyway

00:11:24.730 --> 00:11:29.590
gives us a clue as to why we've
got this colour in our skin.

00:11:29.590 --> 00:11:31.990
And it is to do
with sun protection.

00:11:31.990 --> 00:11:34.240
So in fact, your dark
skin is giving you

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:36.740
some pretty significant
sun protection here.

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:38.770
And Bashir's dark
skin is coming out

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:40.590
as about factor 20 sunscreen.

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:41.090
Naturally.

00:11:41.090 --> 00:11:42.850
So you've got your own
natural sunscreen there.

00:11:42.850 --> 00:11:43.390
Oh, perfect.

00:11:43.390 --> 00:11:43.890
Lovely.

00:11:43.890 --> 00:11:46.150
And if you have got very
pale skin, of course,

00:11:46.150 --> 00:11:50.300
you have to put sunscreen on if
you go out into bright sunshine

00:11:50.300 --> 00:11:53.560
because you could
burn your skin.

00:11:53.560 --> 00:11:55.930
And every single
episode of sunburn

00:11:55.930 --> 00:11:58.450
means that you have a higher
risk of developing skin cancer.

00:11:58.450 --> 00:12:01.730
That's the seriousness
of it a bit later on.

