00:12:12.426 --> 00:12:18.070
See, that connection between
skin colour and sun protection

00:12:18.070 --> 00:12:21.640
gives us a clue as to how this
evolved in humans, as well.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:25.090
So our ancestors who
expanded out of Africa

00:12:25.090 --> 00:12:26.620
would have all had dark skin.

00:12:26.620 --> 00:12:29.470
So the first Asians,
the first Europeans

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:31.000
would all have had dark skin.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.120
And in fact, it's not until
much later that some mutations

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:38.020
started to pop up in genomes so
that skin started to get a bit

00:12:38.020 --> 00:12:41.860
paler, particularly in very,
very northern areas where

00:12:41.860 --> 00:12:45.100
the sun just isn't as bright
as it is in the tropics

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:46.660
and around the Equator.

00:12:46.660 --> 00:12:50.860
And in fact, we still see these
patterns of skin colour today.

00:12:50.860 --> 00:12:54.520
So we still see that people
whose ancestry is predominantly

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:58.450
from those sunnier places of the
world tend to have darker skin.

00:12:58.450 --> 00:13:01.270
And people who've got more
ancestry in the far north

00:13:01.270 --> 00:13:04.270
tend to have paler
skin, as well.

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:07.240
