00:41:11.210 --> 00:41:12.740
So this is fascinating.

00:41:12.740 --> 00:41:16.040
We do seem to be able
to make some reasonably

00:41:16.040 --> 00:41:19.820
good predictions about people
based on their genetics.

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:21.810
But that was a bit of fun.

00:41:21.810 --> 00:41:24.110
It was a lot of fun,
and I got a cupcake.

00:41:24.110 --> 00:41:26.390
But there's a more
serious side to this, too,

00:41:26.390 --> 00:41:32.445
because we can use genetics to
predict our risk of disease.

00:41:32.445 --> 00:41:34.070
I mean, you just
think really carefully

00:41:34.070 --> 00:41:35.840
about how we do
that and whether we

00:41:35.840 --> 00:41:37.940
want to know this information.

00:41:37.940 --> 00:41:40.550
So to help us think through
some of these issues,

00:41:40.550 --> 00:41:45.230
I'd like you to welcome my
friend, bioethicist Professor

00:41:45.230 --> 00:41:46.230
Heather Widdows.

00:41:46.230 --> 00:41:46.730
Heather.

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:49.706
[APPLAUSE]

00:41:51.690 --> 00:41:56.300
Now, Heather, first of
all, what is a bioethicist?

00:41:56.300 --> 00:41:59.630
Well, my job is to think
not about what we can do,

00:41:59.630 --> 00:42:01.020
but about what we should do.

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:02.630
So I think about
the implications

00:42:02.630 --> 00:42:04.390
for all the stuff you've heard.

00:42:04.390 --> 00:42:08.090
And now that we can predict
risk of some diseases--

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:09.810
some better than others--

00:42:09.810 --> 00:42:11.510
what are the
advantages to knowing

00:42:11.510 --> 00:42:13.020
that kind of information?

00:42:13.020 --> 00:42:14.613
Well, some of it is
disease specific.

00:42:14.613 --> 00:42:16.280
So if there's a
treatment, for instance,

00:42:16.280 --> 00:42:18.080
then you need to know.

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:19.850
But there are general
things that people

00:42:19.850 --> 00:42:21.470
think that maybe you
have a right to know,

00:42:21.470 --> 00:42:22.345
that you should know.

00:42:22.345 --> 00:42:24.620
And that will help
you plan your future.

00:42:24.620 --> 00:42:26.960
So that could be things
like lifestyle choices.

00:42:26.960 --> 00:42:29.210
So if you have a disposition,
say, to something

00:42:29.210 --> 00:42:30.920
like a form of
cancer, then you might

00:42:30.920 --> 00:42:33.050
want to plan your life
a bit differently.

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:34.550
So when you're
thinking about things

00:42:34.550 --> 00:42:36.285
like when you want
to have children,

00:42:36.285 --> 00:42:37.660
if you want to
have children, you

00:42:37.660 --> 00:42:39.470
might want to have
children earlier.

00:42:39.470 --> 00:42:41.450
You might want to maybe
do your "bucket list."

00:42:41.450 --> 00:42:43.957
You don't want to wait till
you're retired to go and climb

00:42:43.957 --> 00:42:44.540
Mount Everest.

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:44.930
Yeah.

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:46.472
So it can kind of
help with planning.

00:42:46.472 --> 00:42:47.330
Right.

00:42:47.330 --> 00:42:49.220
You could change your
lifestyle and hopefully

00:42:49.220 --> 00:42:50.613
lessen your risk there.

00:42:50.613 --> 00:42:52.280
But what are the
negatives when it comes

00:42:52.280 --> 00:42:54.290
to knowing your disease risk?

00:42:54.290 --> 00:42:56.480
So just like some people
think you should know,

00:42:56.480 --> 00:42:58.820
other people feel very
strongly that other way.

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:02.300
They think that you should have
an open future, that knowing is

00:43:02.300 --> 00:43:03.950
going to make you
think that you're

00:43:03.950 --> 00:43:06.320
ill when, in fact,
you're very well still.

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:07.880
So even though
you're not ill, you

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:09.490
might start behaving
as if you are.

00:43:09.490 --> 00:43:10.990
And you kind of
wish your life away.

00:43:10.990 --> 00:43:12.710
So for very many
other people, they

00:43:12.710 --> 00:43:16.790
think that, in fact, we
really have a duty or a right

00:43:16.790 --> 00:43:18.500
not to know that's important.

00:43:18.500 --> 00:43:22.340
So we'd like to explore some
of these areas with you.

00:43:22.340 --> 00:43:25.410
And at your feet,
you've got voting cards.

00:43:25.410 --> 00:43:28.070
So when we ask you to vote,
what I'd like you to do

00:43:28.070 --> 00:43:30.440
is hold up your answer
with the answer facing us.

00:43:30.440 --> 00:43:33.400
So we're going to talk
about a number of diseases

00:43:33.400 --> 00:43:36.167
and see what you think,
see how you feel about it.

00:43:36.167 --> 00:43:38.000
Have a good think about
whether you'd really

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:41.090
want to know if you had a
higher risk of developing

00:43:41.090 --> 00:43:42.410
such a disease.

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:46.160
So should we have a think
about early-onset Alzheimer's

00:43:46.160 --> 00:43:46.790
disease?

00:43:46.790 --> 00:43:47.290
Yeah.

00:43:47.290 --> 00:43:49.790
So Alzheimer's is
one form of dementia.

00:43:49.790 --> 00:43:54.135
And usually, the tests will
only tell you susceptibility

00:43:54.135 --> 00:43:54.635
and risk.

00:43:54.635 --> 00:43:57.320
And it's more about a cluster
of genes in the environment.

00:43:57.320 --> 00:43:59.780
So this is something which
would cause memory loss,

00:43:59.780 --> 00:44:02.660
eventually makes it difficult
for you to be independent

00:44:02.660 --> 00:44:04.000
and to look after yourselves.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.260
At the moment, there's
no treatment for it.

00:44:06.260 --> 00:44:10.040
So would you like to know if you
had a higher risk of developing

00:44:10.040 --> 00:44:13.340
early Alzheimer's?

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:14.210
I think there's a--

00:44:14.210 --> 00:44:16.370
I think there's a majority
of yeses, actually.

00:44:16.370 --> 00:44:17.960
But there's quite
a lot of people

00:44:17.960 --> 00:44:19.820
who wouldn't like to know.

00:44:19.820 --> 00:44:21.690
So let's think about
another disease.

00:44:21.690 --> 00:44:22.190
OK.

00:44:22.190 --> 00:44:25.890
So the next one we want to
think about is type 2 diabetes.

00:44:25.890 --> 00:44:28.580
So this is where your
body responds to sugar.

00:44:28.580 --> 00:44:30.710
It can affect your eyesight.

00:44:30.710 --> 00:44:32.810
And it can gradually
get more severe.

00:44:32.810 --> 00:44:35.870
It is a disease where
you can manage it

00:44:35.870 --> 00:44:37.790
very well by lifestyle changes.

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:41.403
So obesity is a key
factor in the disease.

00:44:41.403 --> 00:44:43.820
So knowing means that you
really can change your lifestyle

00:44:43.820 --> 00:44:44.780
to address it.

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:48.260
So who would like to know if
they had a slightly higher risk

00:44:48.260 --> 00:44:51.655
of developing type 2 diabetes?

00:44:51.655 --> 00:44:52.655
That's really different.

00:44:52.655 --> 00:44:53.430
Even more.

00:44:53.430 --> 00:44:53.930
Yeah.

00:44:53.930 --> 00:44:57.653
So the vast, vast majority
of you are saying yes.

00:44:57.653 --> 00:45:00.320
It's important to remember, with
these kind of ethics questions,

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:01.737
there is no right
or wrong answer.

00:45:01.737 --> 00:45:03.420
It's what's right
and wrong for you.

00:45:03.420 --> 00:45:05.630
So let's think about
one final disease.

00:45:05.630 --> 00:45:07.490
And let's think about cancer.

00:45:07.490 --> 00:45:10.400
Now, there are lots of
different types of cancer.

00:45:10.400 --> 00:45:12.290
Some of them are treatable.

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:15.060
Some of them are more
difficult to treat.

00:45:15.060 --> 00:45:21.170
But if you could test for a
high risk of a particular cancer

00:45:21.170 --> 00:45:24.230
where there was a treatment
option, what would

00:45:24.230 --> 00:45:25.580
you feel about that?

00:45:25.580 --> 00:45:28.490
Would you want to know if
you were going to develop

00:45:28.490 --> 00:45:30.020
this particular type of cancer?

00:45:33.010 --> 00:45:34.550
I think it is about 2/3.

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:35.050
Yes.

00:45:35.050 --> 00:45:36.050
And about a third "no."

00:45:36.050 --> 00:45:36.550
Yeah.

00:45:36.550 --> 00:45:38.260
I think that looks--

00:45:38.260 --> 00:45:40.480
now, our roving
reporter, Aoife, is

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:43.930
going to come and ask you some
of your opinions about this

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:44.770
and why you voted--

00:45:44.770 --> 00:45:45.520
Is there anybody--

00:45:45.520 --> 00:45:46.300
--in various ways.

00:45:46.300 --> 00:45:47.770
Is there anybody who'd like
to tell me what they voted

00:45:47.770 --> 00:45:49.240
and why they voted?

00:45:49.240 --> 00:45:50.530
So I'll come around to you.

00:45:50.530 --> 00:45:51.120
Oh, sorry.

00:45:51.120 --> 00:45:52.430
I fall on the stairs, as well.

00:45:52.430 --> 00:45:55.680
And what way did you vote
on the Alzheimer's one?

00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:56.900
I voted no.

00:45:56.900 --> 00:45:59.050
And why did you vote no?

00:45:59.050 --> 00:46:02.500
I think you shouldn't
live knowing in fear.

00:46:02.500 --> 00:46:03.920
You should make
your own choices.

00:46:03.920 --> 00:46:04.360
Yeah.

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:05.020
Very interesting.

00:46:05.020 --> 00:46:07.562
Anybody else who wants to tell
me about one of their answers?

00:46:07.562 --> 00:46:08.120
Yeah?

00:46:08.120 --> 00:46:09.620
But which one?

00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:11.500
I voted yes on Alzheimer's--

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:12.460
Yes?

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:15.220
--because I think it'd be
nice to warn your family--

00:46:15.220 --> 00:46:15.730
OK.

00:46:15.730 --> 00:46:16.510
Very interesting.

00:46:16.510 --> 00:46:17.010
--and to share.

00:46:17.010 --> 00:46:17.510
Yeah.

00:46:17.510 --> 00:46:18.580
Yeah.

00:46:18.580 --> 00:46:20.200
Let's see if there's
somebody up here.

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:20.930
You voted no?

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:21.430
OK.

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:24.160
Do you want to tell us what
did you vote no to and why?

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:27.290
I voted no to the
first one because--

00:46:27.290 --> 00:46:28.120
Alzheimer's.

00:46:28.120 --> 00:46:31.450
Yes, because I didn't
want to know because then

00:46:31.450 --> 00:46:34.150
it would make me feel scared.

00:46:34.150 --> 00:46:36.880
And then I won't enjoy my
life as much as I would have.

00:46:36.880 --> 00:46:39.010
I mean, it's very
sophisticated opinions

00:46:39.010 --> 00:46:40.490
coming from our audience here.

00:46:40.490 --> 00:46:42.115
So give yourselves
a round of applause.

00:46:42.115 --> 00:46:44.290
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:46.170 --> 00:46:48.640
Thank you very much
for doing that with us.

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:51.568
There was some really, really
thoughtful answers there,

00:46:51.568 --> 00:46:52.360
I thought, Heather.

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:53.350
Absolutely.

00:46:53.350 --> 00:46:54.870
Lots of the answers
you came up with

00:46:54.870 --> 00:46:57.520
are exactly the answers
that ethicists talk about.

00:46:57.520 --> 00:46:58.060
Really?

00:46:58.060 --> 00:47:01.210
One really interesting
thing, of course, about DNA

00:47:01.210 --> 00:47:05.230
is that it connects
us with other people.

00:47:05.230 --> 00:47:07.740
So this is something you've
thought about long and hard,

00:47:07.740 --> 00:47:10.780
Heather-- that, in fact, when
you have your DNA sequenced,

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:13.520
it's not just your genes
that you're looking at.

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:14.200
Yeah.

00:47:14.200 --> 00:47:14.920
Absolutely.

00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:18.340
The two key things that
make genetic information so

00:47:18.340 --> 00:47:21.760
different are that it is
shared and it is identifying.

00:47:21.760 --> 00:47:24.440
So it's shared with other
members of your family.

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:26.800
And we don't really know
how to balance that.

00:47:26.800 --> 00:47:28.570
So if we think about
something like,

00:47:28.570 --> 00:47:32.660
you know, testing for the
indicators for breast cancer--

00:47:32.660 --> 00:47:35.710
if you are 15, and
you want to be tested,

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.200
and your mother is
35, 40, and doesn't

00:47:38.200 --> 00:47:41.140
want to know, and you know
that there's kind of cancer

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.863
in the family, if you go,
and get tested, and turn out

00:47:43.863 --> 00:47:45.280
to be positive,
then you will have

00:47:45.280 --> 00:47:48.540
information about your mother
that she does not want.

00:47:48.540 --> 00:47:51.310
And we need to think about
how we ethically manage that.

00:47:51.310 --> 00:47:53.470
It feels like we're
only just catching up

00:47:53.470 --> 00:47:56.500
with the ethics of this
whole area of biology.

00:47:56.500 --> 00:47:59.080
It feels that we're not
really kind of grasping

00:47:59.080 --> 00:48:01.130
how to deal with that
information quite yet.

00:48:01.130 --> 00:48:01.270
Yeah.

00:48:01.270 --> 00:48:01.450
No.

00:48:01.450 --> 00:48:02.642
I don't think we are at all.

00:48:02.642 --> 00:48:03.850
I think that's exactly right.

00:48:03.850 --> 00:48:06.160
You know, the science has
moved on quite dramatically.

00:48:06.160 --> 00:48:08.710
This is all about
unknowns in the future.

00:48:08.710 --> 00:48:10.480
Who will want your information?

00:48:10.480 --> 00:48:12.910
Will it change what you
can do employment-wise?

00:48:12.910 --> 00:48:14.628
Will insurers want it?

00:48:14.628 --> 00:48:16.420
And of course, there
is one particular area

00:48:16.420 --> 00:48:19.510
when a genetic test
is carried out,

00:48:19.510 --> 00:48:21.310
it's actually not
on your own DNA,

00:48:21.310 --> 00:48:24.530
but very much on the DNA
of another individual.

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:27.070
And that's when we test
babies in the womb, when

00:48:27.070 --> 00:48:29.440
we do antenatal testing.

00:48:29.440 --> 00:48:32.080
And we're able to test for
more and more things now.

00:48:32.080 --> 00:48:34.930
But again, some really difficult
decision-making when parents

00:48:34.930 --> 00:48:36.830
are presented with results.

00:48:36.830 --> 00:48:37.460
Absolutely.

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:40.120
So you know, perhaps the
one that's most well known

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:41.650
is a test for Down syndrome.

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:43.480
That happens very routinely.

00:48:43.480 --> 00:48:46.780
So that means that nearly
every pregnant woman in the UK

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:47.660
will have that test.

00:48:47.660 --> 00:48:49.443
And they will be
offered it routinely.

00:48:49.443 --> 00:48:50.860
And they may just
think, oh, well,

00:48:50.860 --> 00:48:53.560
this is just part of getting
ready to have the baby.

00:48:53.560 --> 00:48:56.620
And what they may not realise
is that once that result comes

00:48:56.620 --> 00:48:58.990
back, if that's a
positive result,

00:48:58.990 --> 00:49:01.480
then the only thing to
do is either continue--

00:49:01.480 --> 00:49:03.520
so the tests can
help to prepare--

00:49:03.520 --> 00:49:05.388
or you can end the pregnancy.

00:49:05.388 --> 00:49:07.930
And that may be something that
they hadn't quite realised was

00:49:07.930 --> 00:49:08.440
happening.

00:49:08.440 --> 00:49:10.630
So very difficult decisions.

00:49:10.630 --> 00:49:12.580
I want to introduce
you to somebody

00:49:12.580 --> 00:49:15.910
who did have an antenatal
test for Down syndrome.

00:49:15.910 --> 00:49:16.830
and her daughter.

00:49:16.830 --> 00:49:20.285
So please, will you
welcome Donna and Frankie.

00:49:20.285 --> 00:49:23.135
