We had a blood test.

00:49:40.420 --> 00:49:43.690
And she came back as a high
chance of having Down syndrome.

00:49:43.690 --> 00:49:45.690
We didn't know
until she was born

00:49:45.690 --> 00:49:46.840
that she had Down syndrome.

00:49:46.840 --> 00:49:49.220
But we knew that there
was a high chance of it.

00:49:49.220 --> 00:49:49.970
Yeah.

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:52.260
And did it help you prepare?

00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:53.150
Yeah, definitely.

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:56.150
I mean, I think I went through
my pregnancy, in my head,

00:49:56.150 --> 00:50:00.050
thinking, baby
has Down syndrome.

00:50:00.050 --> 00:50:03.270
It wasn't anything that
was negative for me.

00:50:03.270 --> 00:50:05.175
I was quite happy,
quite excited.

00:50:05.175 --> 00:50:07.170
I've had my first baby.

00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:09.230
It didn't matter
how she came out.

00:50:09.230 --> 00:50:13.660
She was Frankie, weren't you?

00:50:13.660 --> 00:50:15.650
And she's different,
but she's lovely.

00:50:15.650 --> 00:50:16.720
Yeah.

00:50:16.720 --> 00:50:18.920
You know, no child's the same.

00:50:18.920 --> 00:50:22.250
She is so unique
in so many ways.

00:50:22.250 --> 00:50:24.620
But I wouldn't change
a thing about her.

00:50:24.620 --> 00:50:25.450
She's perfect.

00:50:25.450 --> 00:50:25.970
Yeah.

00:50:25.970 --> 00:50:27.050
And we're all unique.

00:50:27.050 --> 00:50:27.950
Exactly.

00:50:27.950 --> 00:50:28.930
Thank you very much--

00:50:28.930 --> 00:50:29.555
Thank you for--

00:50:29.555 --> 00:50:31.417
--Donna, Frankie, and Heather.

00:50:31.417 --> 00:50:34.279
[APPLAUSE]

00:50:40.480 --> 00:50:43.030
So Aoife, we've been
looking at what we can

00:50:43.030 --> 00:50:45.437
do with this new technology.

00:50:45.437 --> 00:50:46.270
You know, it is new.

00:50:46.270 --> 00:50:48.312
And it's getting faster,
and faster, and cheaper,

00:50:48.312 --> 00:50:48.820
and cheaper.

00:50:48.820 --> 00:50:52.270
And we can read DNA, and we
can make some predictions

00:50:52.270 --> 00:50:53.920
about what we're going to be.

00:50:53.920 --> 00:50:57.180
But we can actually
change DNA now, as well.

00:50:57.180 --> 00:50:57.690
Yeah.

00:50:57.690 --> 00:51:00.280
And we have a really
wonderful example of this.

00:51:00.280 --> 00:51:02.020
So if you could please
welcome a leader

00:51:02.020 --> 00:51:04.750
in this field of gene therapy,
from Great Ormond Street

00:51:04.750 --> 00:51:06.490
Hospital, Professor
Bobby Gaspar.

00:51:06.490 --> 00:51:09.400
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:09.400 --> 00:51:11.340
Thank you so much for coming on.

00:51:14.250 --> 00:51:17.130
So you've been working in
the area of gene therapy--

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:20.640
so being able to change
genes to help patients--

00:51:20.640 --> 00:51:22.070
for quite a number of years now.

00:51:22.070 --> 00:51:22.570
Yes.

00:51:22.570 --> 00:51:24.330
Well, I actually I started
right at the beginning,

00:51:24.330 --> 00:51:26.372
when I was a junior doctor
at Great Ormond Street

00:51:26.372 --> 00:51:29.710
Hospital about 25 years ago.

00:51:29.710 --> 00:51:34.860
And really, what we're trying
to do is, in some diseases,

00:51:34.860 --> 00:51:37.595
it comes about because a
gene is defective or missing.

00:51:37.595 --> 00:51:38.970
And what we want
to try and do is

00:51:38.970 --> 00:51:41.880
put a working copy of the
gene back into those cells

00:51:41.880 --> 00:51:43.980
so they now have
the correct gene.

00:51:43.980 --> 00:51:44.710
The gene works.

00:51:44.710 --> 00:51:47.760
It makes the right signals to
be able to correct that disease.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:50.770
So it's a very fundamental
way of correcting diseases.

00:51:50.770 --> 00:51:52.840
So you're really getting
to the root cause.

00:51:52.840 --> 00:51:55.912
And you helped the
first ever patient to be

00:51:55.912 --> 00:51:57.120
helped with the gene therapy.

00:51:57.120 --> 00:51:58.060
First worldwide.

00:51:58.060 --> 00:52:01.253
And he's the first
successfully-treated child

00:52:01.253 --> 00:52:01.920
by gene therapy.

00:52:01.920 --> 00:52:05.300
And our team at University
College and Great Ormond Street

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:07.380
helped treat him back in 2001.

00:52:07.380 --> 00:52:09.600
And he's here this evening
to come and show off

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:11.130
how strong and healthy he is.

00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:12.180
Please welcome Rhys.

00:52:12.180 --> 00:52:14.625
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:18.910
Hello, Rhys.

00:52:18.910 --> 00:52:20.930
I must say you are
looking very healthy.

00:52:20.930 --> 00:52:23.870
We have a picture of you
from about one-year-old,

00:52:23.870 --> 00:52:24.903
I think, up there.

00:52:24.903 --> 00:52:26.320
What you can just
about see, there

00:52:26.320 --> 00:52:28.740
is a plastic bubble around Rhys.

00:52:28.740 --> 00:52:30.960
So you spent a lot of
time in that bubble.

00:52:30.960 --> 00:52:34.270
Well, when I was born, I had
to be put into this bubble

00:52:34.270 --> 00:52:36.970
because I wasn't born
with an immune system.

00:52:36.970 --> 00:52:40.300
And so any sort of bacteria
or viruses in the atmosphere

00:52:40.300 --> 00:52:43.190
that I would inhale
or breathe in,

00:52:43.190 --> 00:52:46.450
it would then harm
me because my system

00:52:46.450 --> 00:52:48.550
wasn't very strong at all.

00:52:48.550 --> 00:52:51.860
And Professor Bobby
Gaspar was your doctor.

00:52:51.860 --> 00:52:52.360
Yes.

00:52:52.360 --> 00:52:52.860
Yeah.

00:52:52.860 --> 00:52:54.130
So what did you do for Rhys?

00:52:54.130 --> 00:52:57.430
Well, Rhys, as he says,
there was a single gene

00:52:57.430 --> 00:53:00.010
that was missing in his bone
marrow, not working properly.

00:53:00.010 --> 00:53:01.390
He couldn't make immune cells.

00:53:01.390 --> 00:53:03.640
And so my colleague
and myself, we

00:53:03.640 --> 00:53:07.090
were working on a new way
of treating this condition

00:53:07.090 --> 00:53:08.680
through gene therapy.

00:53:08.680 --> 00:53:10.720
And that meant taking
Rhys's own cells.

00:53:10.720 --> 00:53:12.640
So he went to the
operating theatre.

00:53:12.640 --> 00:53:15.730
And we took out your
bone marrow stem cells.

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:19.000
And in the lab, we put a
working copy of that gene--

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:20.250
that gene that was missing--

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:23.320
we put a working copy of that
back into his bone marrow cells

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:26.830
and then gave those gene
modified cells back to Rhys.

00:53:26.830 --> 00:53:30.320
And then over a few months, his
immune system starts to grow.

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:34.240
And this was the first time we'd
seen it in any child in the UK.

00:53:34.240 --> 00:53:36.760
And then after
about six months, it

00:53:36.760 --> 00:53:38.510
was growing and
working really well.

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:41.660
So we were really, really
delighted how well it worked.

00:53:41.660 --> 00:53:44.270
And so Rhys, this has
totally changed your life.

00:53:44.270 --> 00:53:45.100
Yeah.

00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:47.260
No, I don't think I'd
be alive, honestly.

00:53:47.260 --> 00:53:51.250
It's such a wonderful
example of how genetics

00:53:51.250 --> 00:53:52.420
can transform medicine.

00:53:52.420 --> 00:53:53.870
And we have these new therapies.

00:53:53.870 --> 00:53:55.750
Well, now that we're
able to identify

00:53:55.750 --> 00:53:58.210
all of these different
genes that cause diseases,

00:53:58.210 --> 00:54:01.870
now we'll see genetic
treatments for eye diseases.

00:54:01.870 --> 00:54:05.010
Certain leukemias can be
treated by genetic therapies.

00:54:05.010 --> 00:54:06.760
And there'll be other
conditions, as well,

00:54:06.760 --> 00:54:08.320
that will be treated
by gene therapy.

00:54:08.320 --> 00:54:09.880
It's such a positive story.

00:54:09.880 --> 00:54:11.500
So thank you so
much, Rhys and Bobby,

00:54:11.500 --> 00:54:13.012
for coming in and
telling us that.

00:54:13.012 --> 00:54:13.988
Thank you.

00:54:13.988 --> 00:54:14.488
Thank you.

00:54:14.488 --> 00:54:16.948
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:19.900 --> 00:54:22.013
Aoife, Rhys's story,
it was just amazing.

00:54:22.013 --> 00:54:22.680
It's incredible.

00:54:22.680 --> 00:54:25.070
And this does feel like a
new frontier in medicine,

00:54:25.070 --> 00:54:27.920
being able to fix faulty genes.

00:54:27.920 --> 00:54:30.710
And I wonder how
far we go with this

00:54:30.710 --> 00:54:34.190
because fixing disease seems
like a very positive thing

00:54:34.190 --> 00:54:34.690
to do.

00:54:34.690 --> 00:54:36.980
But you could make
other changes.

00:54:36.980 --> 00:54:39.490
I mean, parents could be
choosing, I don't know,

00:54:39.490 --> 00:54:42.680
eye colour, skin
colour of their babies.

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:46.260
And that, I think, is a
very, very different issue.

00:54:46.260 --> 00:54:46.760
Definitely.

00:54:46.760 --> 00:54:49.113
I mean, I have a
personal view on that,

00:54:49.113 --> 00:54:50.780
and that is that that
shouldn't be done.

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:53.280
I just don't think it's a
suitable use of the technology.

00:54:53.280 --> 00:54:55.310
And it's something
that should be avoided.

00:54:55.310 --> 00:54:56.810
And this science
and this technology

00:54:56.810 --> 00:54:58.040
is moving really fast.

00:54:58.040 --> 00:55:01.340
So all of you will have to think
about this really carefully

00:55:01.340 --> 00:55:03.620
over the course of your lives.

00:55:03.620 --> 00:55:05.840
Science is fantastic.

00:55:05.840 --> 00:55:08.270
It tells us so much
about the world around us

00:55:08.270 --> 00:55:09.350
and about ourselves.

00:55:09.350 --> 00:55:12.800
And it provides us with
amazing technological tools.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:15.840
But we have to work out how
we're going to use these tools.

00:55:15.840 --> 00:55:18.920
And that's not just a question
for scientists and ethicists.

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:21.560
It's a question for everybody
because this science

00:55:21.560 --> 00:55:24.800
and this technology
belongs to all of us.

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:27.170
And just because
we can do something

00:55:27.170 --> 00:55:28.760
doesn't mean that we should.

00:55:28.760 --> 00:55:31.730
But one thing that we do see in
all of this is that each of us

00:55:31.730 --> 00:55:33.050
is a total one-off.

00:55:33.050 --> 00:55:36.680
Even the twins were
a unique parcel

00:55:36.680 --> 00:55:39.860
of talents, strengths,
weaknesses, foibles,

00:55:39.860 --> 00:55:40.970
and charms.

00:55:40.970 --> 00:55:44.550
We started out
wondering who we were,

00:55:44.550 --> 00:55:49.190
what makes us unique,
what makes you "you."

00:55:49.190 --> 00:55:51.350
And we found an answer to that.

00:55:51.350 --> 00:55:52.670
But it's your past.

00:55:52.670 --> 00:55:56.570
It's all your ancestors who have
passed down their genes to you.

00:55:56.570 --> 00:55:57.928
But it's also your own past.

00:55:57.928 --> 00:55:59.720
What happened to you
in the womb and what's

00:55:59.720 --> 00:56:02.240
happened to you since
you've been born combined

00:56:02.240 --> 00:56:06.560
with a lot of chance, as
well, makes each one of you

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:08.990
a unique individual.

00:56:08.990 --> 00:56:12.680
And there is no such
thing as a perfect human.

00:56:12.680 --> 00:56:14.990
There is no normal human.

00:56:14.990 --> 00:56:18.430
Humanity is all of us.

00:56:18.430 --> 00:56:19.910
Everyone is different.

00:56:19.910 --> 00:56:23.840
And everyone has
something special to give.

00:56:23.840 --> 00:56:24.740
Thank you.

00:56:24.740 --> 00:56:27.790
[APPLAUSE]

